ca. Detroit: Wayne State University Press, 1984.\n* [http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-1551&sug=y New Georgia Encyclopedia article on the Episcopal Church in the U.S. South]\n\n===Historiography===\n* Caldwell, Sandra M., & Caldwell, Ronald J.  ''The History of the Episcopal Church in America, 1607\u20131991: A Bibliography''. (1993).\n* Mills, Frederick V. \"The Colonial Anglican Episcopate: A Historiographical Review.\" ''Anglican and Episcopal History'' 61.3 (1992): 325-345. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/42611493 in JSTOR]\n* Mullin, Robert Bruce. \"Trends in the Study of the History of the Episcopal Church,\" ''Anglican and Episcopal History,'' June 2003, Vol. 72 Issue 2, pp 153\u2013165, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/42612314 in JSTOR]\n\n===Primary sources===\n* Armentrout, Don S., & Slocum, Robert Boak.  ''Documents of Witness: A History of the Episcopal Church, 1782\u20131985''. (1994). New York: Church Hymnal Corporation.\n\n{{ECUSA Provinces}}\n\n[[Category:Episcopal Church (United States)]]\n[[Category:History of Anglicanism|Episcopal Church]]\n[[Category:History of Christianity in the United States|Episcopal Church]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 246-286 \u2192 246\u2013286 (5)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Episcopal_Church_(United_States)"}
{"title_page": "Letitia Plummer", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Letitia Plummer\n|image         = \n|office        = [[Houston City Council]] At-Large Position 4\n|term_start    = January 2, 2020\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Amanda Edwards]]\n|successor     = \n|birth_name    = \n|birth_date    = \n|birth_place   = [[Boston, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   =\n|restingplace = \n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse        = \n|occupation   = [[Dentist]]\n|children      = 3\n|residence     = \n|alma_mater     = [[Spelman College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Baylor College of Dentistry]]\n}}\n'''Letitia Plummer''' is a [[Texas]] politician that currently represents At-Large Position 4 of the [[Houston City Council]]. She is the first [[Muslim]] to be elected to the council.\n\n==Personal life==\nPlummer was born in [[Boston, Massachusetts]] to a [[Indians in Yemen|Yemeni-Indian]] mother and an [[African American]] father. The family moved to [[Houston]] in 1973, and Plummer attended [[Houston Independent School District]] where she graduated from [[DeBakey High School for Health Professions]], formerly known as The High School for Health Professionals. After high school, she attended the historically black college [[Spelman College]] where she was a member of the [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]] sorority. She then returned to Texas and attended [[Baylor College of Dentistry]] and became a practicing [[dentist]]. She owns 2 dental practices in the [[Greater Houston|Houston Metropolitan area]], and has been recognized with the \u201cTop Professionals on the Fast Track\u201d and \u201cHouston\u2019s Top Dentist\u201d awards. Plummer has 3 sons and is a practicing [[Muslim]].<ref>{{cite web |title=City Council At-Large Position 4 |url=https://www.houstontx.gov/council/4/index.html |website=www.houstontx.gov |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=cair>{{cite web |title=CAIR-Houston Congratulates Dr. Letitia Plummer, Houston\u2019s first Muslim Woman Inaugurated to City Council \u2013 CAIR \u2013 Council on American-Islamic Relations |url=https://www.cair.com/press_releases/cair-houston-congratulates-dr-letitia-plummer-houstons-first-muslim-woman-inaugurated-to-city-council/ |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nPlummer was first elected in December 2019 winning 51.9% of the vote against her opponent Anthony Dolcefino, she is the first [[Muslim]] to elected to the [[Houston City Council]].<ref name =ballot>{{cite web |title=Letitia Plummer |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Letitia_Plummer |website=Ballotpedia |accessdate=10 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name = cair/> She was sworn in on January 2, 2020 to represent At-Large Position 4 of the [[Houston City Council]] succeeding [[Amanda Edwards]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Whalen |first1=Emma |title=Houston Runoff Voter Guide 2019: City Council At-Large Position 4 candidates Anthony Dolcefino and Letitia Plummer |url=https://communityimpact.com/houston/heights-river-oaks-montrose/vote/2019/12/03/houston-runoff-voter-guide-2019-city-council-at-large-position-4-candidates-anthony-dolcefino-and-letitia-plummer/ |website=impact |accessdate=10 March 2020 |language=English |date=3 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=ballot/> who [[2020 United States Senate election in Texas|ran]] for [[United States Senate|Senate]]. Plummer is affiliated with the [[Democratic Party (U.S.)|Democratic Party]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Letitia Plummer \u2013 Off the Kuff |url=https://www.offthekuff.com/wp/?tag=letitia-plummer |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Houston City Council members]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Texas Democrats]]\n[[Category:American Muslims]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Boston]]\n[[Category:American dentists]]\n[[Category:Spelman College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Letitia Plummer\n|image         = \n|office        = [[Houston City Council]] At-Large Position 4\n|term_start    = January 2, 2020\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Amanda Edwards]]\n|successor     = \n|birth_name    = \n|birth_date    = \n|birth_place   = [[Boston, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   =\n|restingplace = \n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse        = \n|occupation   = [[Dentist]]\n|children      = 3\n|residence     = \n|alma_mater     = [[Spelman College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Baylor College of Dentistry]]\n}}\n'''Letitia Plummer''' is a [[Texas]] politician that currently represents At-Large Position 4 of the [[Houston City Council]]. She is the first [[Muslim]] to be elected to the council.\n\n==Personal life==\nPlummer was born in [[Boston, Massachusetts]] to a [[Indians in Yemen|Yemeni-Indian]] mother and an [[African American]] father. The family moved to [[Houston]] in 1973, and Plummer attended [[Houston Independent School District]] where she graduated from [[DeBakey High School for Health Professions]], formerly known as The High School for Health Professionals. After high school, she attended the historically black college [[Spelman College]] where she was a member of the Alpha Kappa Alpha sorority. She then returned to Texas and attended [[Baylor College of Dentistry]] and became a practicing [[dentist]]. She owns 2 dental practices in the [[Greater Houston|Houston Metropolitan area]], and has been recognized with the \u201cTop Professionals on the Fast Track\u201d and \u201cHouston\u2019s Top Dentist\u201d awards. Plummer has 3 sons and is a practicing [[Muslim]].<ref>{{cite web |title=City Council At-Large Position 4 |url=https://www.houstontx.gov/council/4/index.html |website=www.houstontx.gov |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=cair>{{cite web |title=CAIR-Houston Congratulates Dr. Letitia Plummer, Houston\u2019s first Muslim Woman Inaugurated to City Council \u2013 CAIR \u2013 Council on American-Islamic Relations |url=https://www.cair.com/press_releases/cair-houston-congratulates-dr-letitia-plummer-houstons-first-muslim-woman-inaugurated-to-city-council/ |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nPlummer was first elected in December 2019 winning 51.9% of the vote against her opponent Anthony Dolcefino, she is the first [[Muslim]] to elected to the [[Houston City Council]].<ref name =ballot>{{cite web |title=Letitia Plummer |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Letitia_Plummer |website=Ballotpedia |accessdate=10 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name = cair/> She was sworn in on January 2, 2020 to represent At-Large Position 4 of the [[Houston City Council]] succeeding [[Amanda Edwards]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Whalen |first1=Emma |title=Houston Runoff Voter Guide 2019: City Council At-Large Position 4 candidates Anthony Dolcefino and Letitia Plummer |url=https://communityimpact.com/houston/heights-river-oaks-montrose/vote/2019/12/03/houston-runoff-voter-guide-2019-city-council-at-large-position-4-candidates-anthony-dolcefino-and-letitia-plummer/ |website=impact |accessdate=10 March 2020 |language=English |date=3 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=ballot/> who [[2020 United States Senate election in Texas|ran]] for [[United States Senate|Senate]]. Plummer is affiliated with the [[Democratic Party (U.S.)|Democratic Party]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Letitia Plummer \u2013 Off the Kuff |url=https://www.offthekuff.com/wp/?tag=letitia-plummer |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Houston City Council members]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Texas Democrats]]\n[[Category:American Muslims]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Boston]]\n[[Category:American dentists]]\n[[Category:Spelman College alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Naraht", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkAlpha Kappa AlphausingFind link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Letitia_Plummer"}
{"title_page": "Hwamyeong LOTTE CASTLE KAISER", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Hwamyeong LOTTE CASTLE KAISER|timestamp=20200406082919|year=2020|month=April|day=6|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Hwamyeong LOTTE CASTLE KAISER|date=6 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Multiple issues|{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}{{Notability|Places|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name = LOTTE CASTLE KAISER\n| image = LOTTE CASTLE.png\n| image_alt = LOTTE CASTLE KAISER symbol and logo\n| floor_count = F.35 - B.4\n| stop_date = 2012\n| architect = LOTTE Construction\n| address = St. Geumgok ([[Hwamyeong-dong]] 2324), [[Buk-gu]], [[Busan]], {{flag|South Korea}} [[South Korea]]\n}}\n\n'''Hwamyeong LOTTE CASTLE KAISER''' ([[Korean language|Korean]]: \ud654\uba85\ub86f\ub370\uce90\uc2ac\uce74\uc774\uc800) is a large apartment complex located in [[Hwamyeong-dong]], [[Buk-gu]], [[Busan]], [[South Korea]].\n\nBuilt in 2012, it is reconstructed from the Hwamyeong Jugong apartments. The complex comprises 48 buildings, and houses 5,239 apartments plus commercial facilities. It is the largest single apartment complex in Busan city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lottecastle.co.kr/apt/quickSearch/list.do#|title=Prestige of Life \ub86f\ub370\uce90\uc2ac|website=www.lottecastle.co.kr|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nIt has a swimming pool, fitness center, indoor golf course, and a private library. The nearest subway is [[Sujeong station]], located just outside the main gate of the complex.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Residential buildings in South Korea]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Hwamyeong LOTTE CASTLE KAISER|timestamp=20200406082919|year=2020|month=April|day=6|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Hwamyeong LOTTE CASTLE KAISER|date=6 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Multiple issues|{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}{{Notability|Places|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name = LOTTE CASTLE KAISER\n| image = LOTTE CASTLE.png\n| image_alt = LOTTE CASTLE KAISER symbol and logo\n| floor_count = F.35 - B.4\n| stop_date = 2012\n| architect = LOTTE Construction\n| address = St. Geumgok ([[Hwamyeong-dong]] 2324), [[Buk-gu]], [[Busan]], {{flag|South Korea}} [[South Korea]]\n}}\n\n'''Hwamyeong LOTTE CASTLE KAISER''' ([[Korean language|Korean]]: \ud654\uba85\ub86f\ub370\uce90\uc2ac\uce74\uc774\uc800) is a large apartment complex located in [[Hwamyeong-dong]], [[Buk-gu]], [[Busan]], [[South Korea]].\n\nBuilt in 2012, it is reconstructed from the Hwamyeong Jugong apartments. The complex comprises 48 buildings, and houses 5,239 apartments plus commercial facilities. It is the largest single apartment complex in Busan city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lottecastle.co.kr/apt/quickSearch/list.do#|title=Prestige of Life \ub86f\ub370\uce90\uc2ac|website=www.lottecastle.co.kr|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nIt has a swimming pool, fitness center, indoor golf course, and a private library. The [[Sujeong]] subway station is located just outside the main gate of the complex.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Residential buildings in South Korea]]\n", "name_user": "MichaelMichael10000", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed sentence so that wikilink goes to the correct article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hwamyeong_LOTTE_CASTLE_KAISER"}
{"title_page": "Barack Obama assassination plot in Tennessee", "text_new": "{{Further|Assassination threats against Barack Obama}}\n{{good article}}\n[[Image:Official portrait of Barack Obama.jpg|thumb|[[Barack Obama]], the [[List of Presidents of the United States|44th]] [[President of the United States]] and target of an alleged assassination plot during his candidacy.]]\nThe '''Barack Obama assassination plot in Tennessee''' was a plot by Paul Schlesselman and Daniel Cowart to [[assassination|assassinate]] [[Barack Obama]], who was then the 2008 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] [[presidential nominee]]. The two men, both [[Neo-Nazism|Neo-Nazis]] [[white power skinheads]], spoke of killing Obama during a planned murder spree of 88 [[African American]]s in [[Tennessee]] (in reference to the [[Nazism|Nazi]] slogan ''[[Nazi salute|Heil Hitler]]''), 14 of whom were to be [[Decapitation|beheaded]] (a reference to the [[Fourteen Words]] slogan), many of whom were young students at an unidentified, predominantly black school.\n\nSchlesselman and Cowart were arrested on October 22, 2008, and found to be in possession of several weapons. The men told authorities of their planned assassination and killing spree, and said they intended to rob a gun store to obtain additional weapons and commit home robberies to help fund the operation. Although the [[United States Secret Service]] said they were taking the plot seriously, authorities were unsure how capable Schlesselman and Cowart were of carrying out the alleged plot. Both plotters pleaded guilty to various federal charges; Judge [[J. Daniel Breen]] of the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Tennessee]] sentenced Schlesselman to 10 years imprisonment on April 15, 2010, and Cowart to 14 years in prison on October 22, 2010.\n\n==Investigation and arrests==\nPaul Schlesselman, 18, of [[Helena\u2013West Helena, Arkansas]], and Daniel Cowart, 20, of [[Bells, Tennessee]], allegedly plotted to assassinate [[Barack Obama]] during his [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"AP1027\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kwtx.com/home/headlines/33403694.html |title=Feds disrupt skinhead plot to assassinate Obama |date=2008-10-27 |accessdate=2008-10-28 |last=Jordan |first=Lara Jakes |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |quote=According to an arrest affidavit, the two men planned to drive their vehicle as fast as they could toward Obama, firing from the windows with high-powered rifles.  The affidavit said the two men planned to wear white tuxedos and top hats during the assassination attempt. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109004252/http://www.kwtx.com/home/headlines/33403694.html |archivedate=2013-11-09 }}</ref> Both [[Neo-Nazism|Neo-Nazis]], Schlesselman and Cowart were introduced to each other via the [[Internet]] in September 2008 by a mutual friend who shared their [[white supremacy|white supremacist]] beliefs.<ref name=\"AP1030\">{{cite news |last1=Baird |first1=Woody |last2=DeMillo |first2=Andrew |title=Authorities say skinhead plot wasn't fully formed |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |date=2008-10-30 |url=http://archive.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2008/10/28/skinhead_plot_news_sweeps_suspects_tenn_hometown/ |accessdate=2017-11-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201034229/http://archive.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2008/10/28/skinhead_plot_news_sweeps_suspects_tenn_hometown/ |archive-date=2017-12-01 |url-status=live }}</ref> Within a month they began planning to kill Obama by driving their vehicle toward him as fast as they could and shooting at him from the windows. The murder was planned as the final act of violence of a killing spree in which the men planned to kill 88 [[African American]]s by gunfire, mostly children at an unidentified, predominantly [[black people|black]] school.<ref name=\"ABC1027\" /><ref name=\"NYT1027\" /> They also planned to behead 14 of the [[88 (number)#In white nationalism|88]] victims. The numbers were chosen for their special significance in the white power movement:<ref name=\"ABC1027\">{{cite news |last=Date |first=Jack |url=http://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/Vote2008/story?id=6122962&page=1 |title=Feds thwart alleged Obama assassination plot |newspaper=[[ABC News]] |date=2008-10-27| accessdate=2008-10-28| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081030022717/http://www.abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/Vote2008/story?id=6122962&page=1| archivedate= 30 October 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> ''88'' means \"[[Hitler salute|Heil Hitler]]\", since H is the eighth letter in the alphabet, and 14 represents the [[Fourteen Words|14-word white supremacist mantra]], \"We must secure the existence of our people and a future for white children.\"<ref name=\"Haberman\">{{cite news |last=Haberman |first=Maggie |title=ATF stops plot to kill Barack Obama |date=2008-10-27 |newspaper=[[New York Post]] |url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/10272008/news/nationalnews/the_plot_to_kill_obama_135558.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081028183217/http://www.nypost.com/seven/10272008/news/nationalnews/the_plot_to_kill_obama_135558.htm |archivedate=2008-10-28 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSchlesselman and Cowart chatted on the Internet about how to carry out the operation. Schlesselman suggested using a [[sawed-off shotgun]] because it would be easy to maneuver; he also said he planned to steal a gun from his father.<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> Prior to their arrest, the men decorated their car with a [[Swastika#Nazism|swastika]] and drew the numbers 88 and 14 on their hood using window chalk.<ref name=\"ABC1027\" /> Authorities believe the men may have planned to move from state to state to choose their victims. They also planned to wear white [[Black tie|tuxedos]] and [[top hat]]s during the assassination attempt.<ref name=\"AP1027\" />\n\n[[Image:Paul Schlesselman and Daniel Cowart.jpg|left|thumb|The convicted assassination plotters, Paul Schlesselman (left) and Daniel Cowart]] \nOn October 22, Schlesselman and Cowart shot at a [[Stained glass|glass window]] on the front door of the Allen Baptist Church in [[Brownsville, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"fbi_20120408\">{{cite web | url=https://www.fbi.gov/memphis/press-releases/2010/me102210.htm | title=Tennessee Man Sentenced for Conspiring to Commit Murders of African-Americans | publisher=FBI | work=2010 Press Release | date=October 22, 2010 | accessdate=May 8, 2012 | quote=Cowart admitted that he and Schlesselman also conspired to burglarize a federally licensed firearms dealer to obtain additional weapons for their scheme. He also admitted to transporting a sawed-off shotgun from Arkansas to Tennessee for the purpose of committing felonies. Cowart additionally admitted to shooting the window of the Allen Baptist Church in Brownsville, Tenn. | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120923043329/http://www.fbi.gov/memphis/press-releases/2010/me102210.htm | archive-date=September 23, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> The two men bragged to a female friend about the shooting; the friend told her mother, who notified the [[Haywood County, Tennessee|Haywood County]] [[Sheriffs in the United States#Tennessee|Sheriff's Department]]. Investigators traced the shell casings to Schlesselman and Cowart, and notified the [[Crockett County, Tennessee|Crockett County]] Sheriff's Department, who took the pair into custody after spotting the swastikas, slurs and 88 and 14 numbers on their car.<ref name=\"AP1030\" /><ref name=\"ABC1027\" />\n\nPolice seized a [[rifle]], a sawed-off shotgun and three [[Handgun|pistols]] from the men at the time of the arrest. They were detained in Bells, Tennessee for a few days before being moved to another facility.<ref name=\"AP1027\" /> During interrogation, the men told authorities of their plan to kill Obama.<ref name=\"NYT1027\">{{cite news |last=Lichtblau |first=Eric |author-link=Eric Lichtblau |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/28/us/politics/28plot.html?scp=1&sq=Daniel%20Cowart&st=cse |title=Arrests in plan to kill Obama and black schoolchildren |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2008-10-27 |accessdate=2008-10-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113031622/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/28/us/politics/28plot.html?scp=1&sq=Daniel%20Cowart&st=cse |archive-date=2013-11-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives]] handled the initial federal investigation of the case.<ref name=\"Haberman\"/> The [[United States Secret Service]] became involved in the investigation once the [[assassination]] plot was discovered.<ref name=\"AP1027\" /> The [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] was also involved in the investigation.<ref name=\"memphis.fbi.gov\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20100109102907/http://memphis.fbi.gov/dojpressrel/pressrel08/me112008.htm Federal Bureau of Investigation \u2013 Memphis Field Division \u2013 Press Release \u2013 Department of Justice<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Both men were charged with illegal possession of a sawed-off shotgun, conspiracy to rob a firearms dealer and making threats against a presidential candidate; a superseding indictment additionally charged the pair with civil rights conspiracy and conspiracy, and charged Cowart with destruction of religious property and a related firearms charge.<ref name=\"memphis.fbi.gov\"/> Authorities have found no evidence that anyone besides the two men were involved in the plot, but as of October 2008 authorities were said to be investigating the possibility.<ref name=\"NYT1027\" />\n{{wikinewspar|Two men arrested in Tennessee for plot to kill Obama and school children}}\nBoth Schlesselman and Cowart acknowledged that they would be killed as a result of the murders and insisted they were willing to die.<ref name=\"AP1027\" /> Authorities said the pair planned to break into a gun shop to steal more weapons for their attack, and also bought nylon [[rope]] and [[Balaclava (clothing)|ski masks]] at [[Walmart]] to use in a [[robbery]] or [[home invasion]] to fund the spree.<ref name=\"AP1027\" /> Schlesselman and Cowart asked a friend to drive them to a house they planned to rob, but they cancelled the robbery after getting scared by a dog and two vehicles in the driveway.<ref name=\"AP1030\" />\n\n==Assessment of threat==\nSecret Service and other authorities said they were treating the plot very seriously, but acknowledged it did not appear to have moved to an advanced stage.<ref name=\"NYT1027\" /> Authorities said there did not appear to be any formal assassination plan and said they were unable to immediately assess how capable the men were of carrying out the attack.<ref name=\"AP1027\" /> Federal authorities told the [[Associated Press]] they did not believe Schlesselman and Cowart had the means to carry out their threat.<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> Barack Obama did not have any campaign appearances planned for Tennessee.<ref name=\"NYT1027\" /> One federal law enforcement official told the AP that  plans did not include Obama's schedule or a specific time and place for the assassination because, \"I don't think they had that level of detail.\"<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> Authorities said they made several mistakes during their planning, including drawing too much attention to themselves with their car markings. Authorities also felt their inability to carry out a home robbery together indicated they would be unable to carry out a sophisticated assassination plot.<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> When asked whether the alleged threats were real, Daniel Cowart's lawyer, Joe H. Byrd, told reporters, \"White top hats and tuxedos? You tell me.\"<ref name=\"AP1106\">{{Citation |last=Baird |first=Woody |url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5jsCEnrVzDQoU5tg63njLNy0UTDNAD949NSQ00 |title=Skinheads plead not guilty in alleged Obama plot |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |date=2009-11-06 |accessdate=2008-11-07}}{{Dead link|date=November 2012|bot=Legobot}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n | quote  = \"They sound crazy, like a really bad movie{{spaced ndash}}Quentin Tarantino gone awry. You listen to that, and you say, 'In a hundred thousand years, they never would have reached Obama.' But the reality is, they might have walked into a black high school and killed 20, 30, 40 people before anybody knew who they were.\"\n | source = '''Mark Potok, director of the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]]'''<ref name=\"WP0111\">{{Citation |last=Johnson |first=Carrie |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/10/AR2009011002039_2.html?hpid=moreheadlines |title=Bad Economy May Fuel Hate Groups, Experts Warn |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2009-01-11 |accessdate=2009-01-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107100929/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/10/AR2009011002039_2.html?hpid=moreheadlines |archive-date=2012-11-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n | align = left\n| width = 195px\n }}\nFred Fielder, police chief in Helena\u2013West Helena, Arkansas, said the alleged plot in Tennessee particularly concerned him due to the fact that 66 percent of the city's 12,200 population are African American; he said to reporters, \"Predominantly black school, take your pick.\"<ref name=\"AP1027\" /> Mark Potok, director of the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]], described the plans and weapons arsenal as frightening, but said, \"With the part about wearing top hats&nbsp;... it gets a bit hard to take them seriously.\"<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> Nevertheless, Potok said \"the reality is, they might have walked into a black high school and killed 20, 30, 40 people before anybody knew who they were\".<ref name=\"WP0111\" /> An editorial in ''[[The Daily News Journal]]'' in [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee]], said the plot emphasized a dark undercurrent of racism still alive in the United States, but said their chances of killing Obama were \"almost nil. Their plot was so disorganized they appear to be candidates for 'dumb criminals', not calculating assassins.\"<ref>[http://www.dnj.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081030/OPINION01/810300305 \"Editorial: Foiled plot revives pain of racism.\"]{{dead link|date=December 2015}} ''[[The Daily News Journal]]'', October 30, 2008. Retrieved on 2008-11-07.</ref>\n\nDespite initial concerns about the plot, the Obama campaign was not immediately notified of the alleged plot; an Obama aide told [[ABC News]], \"They were given no heads up.\"<ref>{{Citation |last= Stephanopoulos |first=George |author-link=George Stephanopoulos |url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/george/2008/10/obama-agents-no.html |title=Obama not told about alleged assassination plot. |newspaper=[[ABC News]] |date=2008-10-27 |accessdate=2008-10-28| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081030012237/http://blogs.abcnews.com/george/2008/10/obama-agents-no.html| archivedate= 30 October 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> Concerns were already strong about possible plots against Obama due to his status as the first African American presidential nominee for a major political party. The senator had been receiving Secret Service protection since May 2007, which was the earliest for any candidate, and authorities had already foiled an [[Barack Obama assassination plot in Denver|alleged assassination plot]] at the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]] in [[Denver]], [[Colorado]].<ref name=\"NYT1027\" />\n\n==Histories of plotters==\n\n===Paul Schlesselman===\nPaul Schlesselman is of [[German-American|German descent]] and was a high school dropout raised by a single father in [[Helena\u2013West Helena, Arkansas]]. He hated his small [[Arkansas Delta|Delta]] region hometown because of its predominantly black population. He had never had any problems with the law prior to the alleged Obama plot. He had a strong affinity for drinking and smoking.<ref name=\"ArkDemGaz1029\">{{Citation |last=Krupa |first=John |url=http://m.arkansasonline.com/news/2008/oct/29/teen-plot-lists-drinking-his-job-20081029/ |title=Teen in plot lists drinking as his job |newspaper=[[Arkansas Democrat-Gazette]] |date=2008-10-29 |accessdate=2010-01-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707162133/http://m.arkansasonline.com/news/2008/oct/29/teen-plot-lists-drinking-his-job-20081029/ |archive-date=2011-07-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSchlesselman publicly claimed white people were the [[master race]] and would often say \"[[Sieg Heil]]\" and \"[[Heil Hitler]].\"<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> He spoke out against Obama, saying things like, \"Obama would make the world suffer.\"<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> His [[Anti-racism|anti-racist]] sister Kayla, who is two years younger than Paul, often argued with him about his racial beliefs. A few days before his arrest, a neighbor said he heard semiautomatic gunfire coming from an open field behind Schlesselman's house.<ref name=\"ArkDemGaz1029\" /> After his arrest, Schlesselman's family expressed doubt that he seriously intended to carry out the plot; his father, Mike, said, \"I think it's just a lot of talk. He would never do something like this.\"<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> Kayla said she spoke with her brother after the charges were made public, and that Paul \"said he's sorry about everything he's done.\"<ref name=\"AP1030\" />\n\n===Daniel Cowart===\nDaniel Cowart is of [[English-Americans|English descent]] and was raised in [[Bells, Tennessee]]. He had a strong interest in computers and had no criminal record. Cowart attended [[Jackson Christian School]] until 2006, but did not graduate.  He was expelled from Jackson Christian after calling in a bomb threat. He applied for [[Jackson State Community College]] to study computers but, although his family believed he was indeed attending the school, he never provided documentation or pursued other steps to enroll there. Cowart moved to [[Texas]] in the spring of 2007 to live with friends he met on the Internet, but was unable to find work and returned to Bells to live with his grandparents a month later.<ref name=\"Jackson1029\">{{Citation |last=Martin |first=Mariann |title=Image of Daniel Cowart not familiar to those he knew in Bells |newspaper=[[The Jackson Sun]] |date=2008-10-29}}</ref> Cowart worked at a Bells grocery store called the Bells Market Place for one year until May 2007 before moving to Texas for a brief time. Cowart worked and got along with several minority co-workers, who later expressed shock at his arrest. Mitchell Twitty, a black former co-worker, said of Cowart, \"He treated me like we were best friends. I never, ever heard him make a racist remark.\"<ref name=\"Jackson1030\">{{Citation |last=Martin |first=Mariann |title=Minority coworkers say Cowart was always friendly, respectful. |newspaper=[[The Jackson Sun]] |date=2008-10-30}}</ref> Twitty said Cowart tended to keep to himself and at times acted \"a little strange.\"<ref name=\"Jackson1030\" /> Other co-workers described him as hard-working and friendly, but said he did not have many friends. One family friend thought he was intelligent and full of potential: \"I always saw him as a doctor or lawyer, or even a senator. He even had the potential to become what Obama is, running for president.\"<ref name=\"Jackson1030\" />\n\nAccording to the Southern Poverty Law Center, Cowart belonged to the Supreme White Alliance, a white supremacist group. A photograph of Cowart celebrating the birthday of [[Adolf Hitler]] with other members was on the group's website.<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> On the group's social networking site, Cowart described himself as \"easygoing and easy to get along with, as long as you are white!\"<ref name=\"ArkDemGaz1029\" /> Cowart was allegedly kicked out of the group sometime prior to his arrest. The club's president, Steve Edwards of [[Central City, Kentucky]], resigned due to the negative press following Cowart's arrest. Although Edwards acknowledged Cowart's membership, he said the group had no part in the plan, and claimed that the media exaggerated Cowart's connection to the group.<ref name=\"AP1030\" />\n\n==Trials==\n[[Image:Schlesselmancowarttrial.jpg|thumb|A court drawing of the first hearing and not guilty pleas of Paul Schlesselman (middle) and Daniel Cowart (right)]]\nA grand jury indicted Paul Schlesselman and Daniel Cowart on November 5, 2008, on federal charges of threatening to kill and inflict bodily harm upon a major presidential candidate, conspiracy, interstate unlawful transportation of an unregistered firearm, interstate transportation of a firearm with the intent to commit a felony, transporting a short-barreled shotgun across state lines without a license and unlawful possession of a short-barreled shotgun. Cowart was also charged with damaging religious property and use of a firearm during a crime of violence.<ref>{{Citation |last=Martin |first=Mariann |title=2 men charged in Obama plot face additional counts |newspaper=[[The Jackson Sun]] |date=2008-11-21}}</ref> On November 6, Schlesselman and Cowart pleaded not guilty before a federal magistrate in [[Memphis, Tennessee]]. The two were placed into federal custody without bail. The charges carry a maximum punishment of 50 years in prison and $540,000 in fines.<ref name=\"AP1106\" />\n\nAt the request of federal authorities, the men were placed on [[lockdown]] in their [[Obion County, Tennessee]], jail cell for their own safety. The two men could leave their cell for only one hour to watch television or use the phone; authorities said they had caused no problems during their time in the jail.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5jsCEnrVzDQoU5tg63njLNy0UTDNAD94BP9TG0 |title=2 accused of threatening Obama kept on lockdown |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |date=2008-11-09 |accessdate=2008-11-10}}{{Dead link|date=November 2012|bot=Legobot}}</ref>\n\nCowart's lawyer argued in a November 13 petition that the grand jury was racially stacked against him because it included only two white members, while \"21 were African-American or of another race or races\".<ref name=\"AP1113\" /> Cowart's attorney argued his indictment should be dismissed because jury could not \"under the most modest constitutional scrutiny&nbsp;... be considered fair, impartial and unprejudiced.\"<ref name=\"AP1113\" /> In February 2009, a federal judge granted Schlesselman and Cowart limited access to court records on the grand jury selection and gave them permission to question procedures for selecting jurors. However, their defense attorneys were not allowed to challenge the resulting racial makeup of the actual jury.<ref>{{Citation |last=Chism |first=Michelle |url=http://www.todaysthv.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=79876&catid=2 |title=Arkansan Charged In Skinhead Plot Granted Access To Court Records |date=2009-02-09 |accessdate=2009-02-09 |newspaper=[[KTHV]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090821022841/http://www.todaysthv.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=79876&catid=2 |archive-date=2009-08-21 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also in February 2009, Schlesselman's lawyer asked the court to dismiss statements he previously gave police and evidence that he contended was wrongfully seized during searches of his home and another residence.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.waaytv.com/Global/story.asp?S=9843627 |title=Man accused in Obama plot wants evidence tossed |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |date=2009-02-14 |accessdate=2009-02-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217234641/http://www.waaytv.com/global/story.asp?s=9843627 |archive-date=2009-02-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Judge [[J. Daniel Breen]] of the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Tennessee]] refused this request in April.<ref>{{Citation|title=Judge Won't Toss Evidence in Plot Against Obama - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=2009-06-08}}</ref> Schlesselman's counsel argued his assassination threat charges should be dropped because he said the alleged comments were made while in custody, so he could not have carried them out and they were not a \"true threat\". Judge Breen rejected that argument in March 2009.<ref>{{Citation|last=Buser |first=Lawrence |title=Judge refuses to dismiss charge in Obama threat |date=2009-03-25 |work=[[The Commercial Appeal]] |location=Memphis, Tennessee |url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2009/mar/25/judge-refuses-dismiss-charge-obama-threat/ |accessdate=2009-03-27 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531054556/http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2009/mar/25/judge-refuses-dismiss-charge-obama-threat/ |archivedate=2009-05-31 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{Wikinews|Judge refuses to dismiss charge against Barack Obama assassination plotter}}\nThe prosecution asked for two separate trials, which were expected to take place in [[Jackson, Tennessee]], the area where the alleged crimes occurred.<ref name=\"AP1113\">{{Citation |last=Baird |first=Woody |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/11/13/national/main4601657.shtml |title=Man charged in Obama plot says grand jury skewed |newspaper=CBS |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=2008-11-13 |accessdate=2008-11-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101115154856/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/11/13/national/main4601657.shtml |archive-date=2010-11-15 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/jacksonsun/access/1866154531.html?FMT=ABS&amp;date=Sep+12,+2009 | work=The Jackson Sun | first=Mariann | last=Martin | title=Separate trials sought in alleged Obama plot | date=2009-09-12 | access-date=2020-01-30 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024133434/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/jacksonsun/access/1866154531.html?FMT=ABS&date=Sep+12,+2009 | archive-date=2012-10-24 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Guilty pleas and sentencing==\nSchlesselman pleaded guilty to two counts in the indictment against him plus one count of an information on January 14, 2010, with an agreed-upon sentence of ten years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2010/jan/14/skinhead-pleads-guilty-conspiring-kill-black-peopl |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615175713/http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2010/jan/14/skinhead-pleads-guilty-conspiring-kill-black-peopl |archivedate=June 15, 2011 |url-status=dead |title='Skinhead' pleads guilty to conspiring to kill black people, threatening Obama |work=commercialappeal.com |author=Staff writer |date=January 14, 2010}}</ref> Cowart pleaded guilty to eight of the nine counts in the superseding indictment on March 29, 2010.<ref>{{Citation |last=Dunlap |first=Stanley |title=Obama plot suspect enters plea |date=2010-03-29 |newspaper=[[The Jackson Sun|Jackson Sun]]}}</ref> On April 15, 2010, Judge Breen sentenced Schlesselman to 10 years in federal prison.<ref>{{cite web|title=Obama assassination plot: Paul Schlesselman sentenced to 10 years for plotting murder spree|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/2010/0/16/2010-04-16_obama_assassination_plot_paul_schlesselman_sentenced_to_10_years_for_plotting_mu.html|work=New York Daily News|accessdate=January 9, 2011|date=April 16, 2010}}{{dead link|date=December 2015}}</ref> Judge Breen sentenced Cowart to 14 years in prison on October 22, 2010.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://memphis.fbi.gov/dojpressrel/pressrel10/me102210.htm |title=Tennessee Man Sentenced for Conspiring to Commit Murders of African-Americans |publisher=Federal Bureau of Investigation, Memphis |date=October 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20110805165411/http://memphis.fbi.gov/dojpressrel/pressrel10/me102210.htm |archivedate=August 5, 2011 }}</ref> The U.S. Justice Department said that Cowart could have been sentenced to a maximum 75 years, and Cowart was originally to be sentenced on August 13.<ref>{{cite web|title=Man who plotted to kill Obama to be sentenced |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2010-08-13/justice/tennessee.obama.plot_1_paul-schlesselman-daniel-cowart-west-helena?_s=PM:CRIME |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100915063447/http://articles.cnn.com/2010-08-13/justice/tennessee.obama.plot_1_paul-schlesselman-daniel-cowart-west-helena?_s=PM%3ACRIME |archivedate=September 15, 2010 |url-status=dead |publisher=CNN |date=August 13, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Incarceration==\nSchlesselman served his sentence at the medium-security [[Federal Correctional Institution, McKean|Federal Correctional Institution in McKean, Pennsylvania]], and was released in July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inmate locator: Paul Schlesselman |url=http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=NameSearch&needingMoreList=false&FirstName=paul&Middle=&LastName=schlesselman&Race=U&Sex=U&Age=&x=0&y=0 |publisher=Federal Bureau of Prisons |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629182205/http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=NameSearch&needingMoreList=false&FirstName=paul&Middle=&LastName=schlesselman&Race=U&Sex=U&Age=&x=0&y=0 |archivedate=June 29, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Cowart is serving his sentence at the medium-security [[Federal Correctional Institution, Williamsburg|Federal Correctional Institution in Williamsburg, South Carolina]], and is scheduled for release in 2021.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inmate locator: Register #22540-076 |url=http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=22540-076&x=56&y=20 |publisher=Federal Bureau of Prisons |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629182214/http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=22540-076&x=56&y=20 |archivedate=June 29, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/barackobama/5967942/Barack-Obama-faces-30-death-threats-a-day-stretching-US-Secret-Service.html Barack Obama Faces 30 Death Threats a day, Stretching US Secret Service] by Toby Harnden, ''Daily Telegraph'', August 3, 2009\n{{Barack Obama}}\n{{Neo-Nazism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barack Obama Assassination Plot In Tennessee}}\n[[Category:2008 in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Attempted assassinations of Presidents of the United States|Obama]]\n[[Category:Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|Assassination plot in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Crimes in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Neo-Nazism in the United States]]\n[[Category:October 2008 crimes]]\n[[Category:Terrorism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in the United States in 2008]]\n[[Category:White nationalism in the United States]]\n[[Category:White nationalist terrorism]]\n[[Category:White supremacy in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Further|Assassination threats against Barack Obama}}\n{{good article}}\n[[Image:Official portrait of Barack Obama.jpg|thumb|[[Barack Obama]], the [[List of Presidents of the United States|44th]] [[President of the United States]] and target of an alleged assassination plot during his candidacy.]]\nThe '''Barack Obama assassination plot in Tennessee''' was a plot by Paul Schlesselman and Daniel Cowart to [[assassination|assassinate]] [[Barack Obama]], who was then the 2008 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] [[presidential nominee]]. The two men, both [[Neo-Nazism|Neo-Nazis]] [[white power skinheads]], spoke of killing Obama during a planned murder spree of 88 [[African American]]s in [[Tennessee]] (in reference to the [[Nazism|Nazi]] slogan ''[[Nazi salute|Heil Hitler]]''), 14 of whom were to be [[Decapitation|beheaded]] (a reference to the [[Fourteen Words]] slogan), many of whom were young students at an unidentified, predominantly black school.\n\nSchlesselman and Cowart were arrested on October 22, 2008, and found to be in possession of several weapons. The men told authorities of their planned assassination and killing spree, and said they intended to rob a gun store to obtain additional weapons and commit home robberies to help fund the operation. Although the [[United States Secret Service]] said they were taking the plot seriously, authorities were unsure how capable Schlesselman and Cowart were of carrying out the alleged plot. Both plotters pleaded guilty to various federal charges; Judge [[J. Daniel Breen]] of the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Tennessee]] sentenced Schlesselman to 10 years imprisonment on April 15, 2010, and Cowart to 14 years in prison on October 22, 2010.\n\n==Investigation and arrests==\nPaul Schlesselman, 18, of [[Helena\u2013West Helena, Arkansas]], and Daniel Cowart, 20, of [[Bells, Tennessee]], allegedly plotted to assassinate [[Barack Obama]] during his [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"AP1027\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kwtx.com/home/headlines/33403694.html |title=Feds disrupt skinhead plot to assassinate Obama |date=2008-10-27 |accessdate=2008-10-28 |last=Jordan |first=Lara Jakes |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |quote=According to an arrest affidavit, the two men planned to drive their vehicle as fast as they could toward Obama, firing from the windows with high-powered rifles.  The affidavit said the two men planned to wear white tuxedos and top hats during the assassination attempt. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109004252/http://www.kwtx.com/home/headlines/33403694.html |archivedate=2013-11-09 }}</ref> Both [[Neo-Nazism|Neo-Nazis]], Schlesselman and Cowart were introduced to each other via the [[Internet]] in September 2008 by a mutual friend who shared their [[white supremacy|white supremacist]] beliefs.<ref name=\"AP1030\">{{cite news |last1=Baird |first1=Woody |last2=DeMillo |first2=Andrew |title=Authorities say skinhead plot wasn't fully formed |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |date=2008-10-30 |url=http://archive.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2008/10/28/skinhead_plot_news_sweeps_suspects_tenn_hometown/ |accessdate=2017-11-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201034229/http://archive.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2008/10/28/skinhead_plot_news_sweeps_suspects_tenn_hometown/ |archive-date=2017-12-01 |url-status=live }}</ref> Within a month they began planning to kill Obama by driving their vehicle toward him as fast as they could and shooting at him from the windows. The murder was planned as the final act of violence of a killing spree in which the men planned to kill 88 [[African American]]s by gunfire, mostly children at an unidentified, predominantly [[black people|black]] school.<ref name=\"ABC1027\" /><ref name=\"NYT1027\" /> They also planned to behead 14 of the [[88 (number)#In white nationalism|88]] victims. The numbers were chosen for their special significance in the white power movement:<ref name=\"ABC1027\">{{cite news |last=Date |first=Jack |url=http://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/Vote2008/story?id=6122962&page=1 |title=Feds thwart alleged Obama assassination plot |newspaper=[[ABC News]] |date=2008-10-27| accessdate=2008-10-28| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081030022717/http://www.abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/Vote2008/story?id=6122962&page=1| archivedate= 30 October 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> ''88'' means \"[[Hitler salute|Heil Hitler]]\", since H is the eighth letter in the alphabet, and 14 represents the [[Fourteen Words|14-word white supremacist mantra]], \"We must secure the existence of our people and a future for white children.\"<ref name=\"Haberman\">{{cite news |last=Haberman |first=Maggie |title=ATF stops plot to kill Barack Obama |date=2008-10-27 |newspaper=[[New York Post]] |url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/10272008/news/nationalnews/the_plot_to_kill_obama_135558.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081028183217/http://www.nypost.com/seven/10272008/news/nationalnews/the_plot_to_kill_obama_135558.htm |archivedate=2008-10-28 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSchlesselman and Cowart chatted on the Internet about how to carry out the operation. Schlesselman suggested using a [[sawed-off shotgun]] because it would be easy to maneuver; he also said he planned to steal a gun from his father.<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> Prior to their arrest, the men decorated their car with a [[Swastika#Nazism|swastika]] and drew the numbers 88 and 14 on their hood using window chalk.<ref name=\"ABC1027\" /> Authorities believe the men may have planned to move from state to state to choose their victims. They also planned to wear white [[Black tie|tuxedos]] and [[top hat]]s during the assassination attempt.<ref name=\"AP1027\" />\n\n[[Image:Paul Schlesselman and Daniel Cowart.jpg|left|thumb|The convicted assassination plotters, Paul Schlesselman (left) and Daniel Cowart]] \nOn October 22, Schlesselman and Cowart shot at a [[Stained glass|glass window]] on the front door of the Allen Baptist Church in [[Brownsville, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"fbi_20120408\">{{cite web | url=https://www.fbi.gov/memphis/press-releases/2010/me102210.htm | title=Tennessee Man Sentenced for Conspiring to Commit Murders of African-Americans | publisher=FBI | work=2010 Press Release | date=October 22, 2010 | accessdate=May 8, 2012 | quote=Cowart admitted that he and Schlesselman also conspired to burglarize a federally licensed firearms dealer to obtain additional weapons for their scheme. He also admitted to transporting a sawed-off shotgun from Arkansas to Tennessee for the purpose of committing felonies. Cowart additionally admitted to shooting the window of the Allen Baptist Church in Brownsville, Tenn. | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120923043329/http://www.fbi.gov/memphis/press-releases/2010/me102210.htm | archive-date=September 23, 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> The two men bragged to a female friend about the shooting; the friend told her mother, who notified the [[Haywood County, Tennessee|Haywood County]] [[Sheriffs in the United States#Tennessee|Sheriff's Department]]. Investigators traced the shell casings to Schlesselman and Cowart, and notified the [[Crockett County, Tennessee|Crockett County]] Sheriff's Department, who took the pair into custody after spotting the swastikas, slurs and 88 and 14 numbers on their car.<ref name=\"AP1030\" /><ref name=\"ABC1027\" />\n\nPolice seized a [[rifle]], a sawed-off shotgun and three [[Handgun|pistols]] from the men at the time of the arrest. They were detained in Bells, Tennessee for a few days before being moved to another facility.<ref name=\"AP1027\" /> During interrogation, the men told authorities of their plan to kill Obama.<ref name=\"NYT1027\">{{cite news |last=Lichtblau |first=Eric |author-link=Eric Lichtblau |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/28/us/politics/28plot.html?scp=1&sq=Daniel%20Cowart&st=cse |title=Arrests in plan to kill Obama and black schoolchildren |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2008-10-27 |accessdate=2008-10-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113031622/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/28/us/politics/28plot.html?scp=1&sq=Daniel%20Cowart&st=cse |archive-date=2013-11-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives]] handled the initial federal investigation of the case.<ref name=\"Haberman\"/> The [[United States Secret Service]] became involved in the investigation once the [[assassination]] plot was discovered.<ref name=\"AP1027\" /> The [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] was also involved in the investigation.<ref name=\"memphis.fbi.gov\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20100109102907/http://memphis.fbi.gov/dojpressrel/pressrel08/me112008.htm Federal Bureau of Investigation \u2013 Memphis Field Division \u2013 Press Release \u2013 Department of Justice<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Both men were charged with illegal possession of a sawed-off shotgun, conspiracy to rob a firearms dealer and making threats against a presidential candidate; a superseding indictment additionally charged the pair with civil rights conspiracy and conspiracy, and charged Cowart with destruction of religious property and a related firearms charge.<ref name=\"memphis.fbi.gov\"/> Authorities have found no evidence that anyone besides the two men were involved in the plot, but as of October 2008 authorities were said to be investigating the possibility.<ref name=\"NYT1027\" />\n{{wikinewspar|Two men arrested in Tennessee for plot to kill Obama and school children}}\nBoth Schlesselman and Cowart acknowledged that they would be killed as a result of the murders and insisted they were willing to die.<ref name=\"AP1027\" /> Authorities said the pair planned to break into a gun shop to steal more weapons for their attack, and also bought nylon [[rope]] and [[Balaclava (clothing)|ski masks]] at [[Walmart]] to use in a [[robbery]] or [[home invasion]] to fund the spree.<ref name=\"AP1027\" /> Schlesselman and Cowart asked a friend to drive them to a house they planned to rob, but they cancelled the robbery after getting scared by a dog and two vehicles in the driveway.<ref name=\"AP1030\" />\n\n==Assessment of threat==\nSecret Service and other authorities said they were treating the plot very seriously, but acknowledged it did not appear to have moved to an advanced stage.<ref name=\"NYT1027\" /> Authorities said there did not appear to be any formal assassination plan and said they were unable to immediately assess how capable the men were of carrying out the attack.<ref name=\"AP1027\" /> Federal authorities told the [[Associated Press]] they did not believe Schlesselman and Cowart had the means to carry out their threat.<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> Barack Obama did not have any campaign appearances planned for Tennessee.<ref name=\"NYT1027\" /> One federal law enforcement official told the AP that  plans did not include Obama's schedule or a specific time and place for the assassination because, \"I don't think they had that level of detail.\"<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> Authorities said they made several mistakes during their planning, including drawing too much attention to themselves with their car markings. Authorities also felt their inability to carry out a home robbery together indicated they would be unable to carry out a sophisticated assassination plot.<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> When asked whether the alleged threats were real, Daniel Cowart's lawyer, Joe H. Byrd, told reporters, \"White top hats and tuxedos? You tell me.\"<ref name=\"AP1106\">{{Citation |last=Baird |first=Woody |url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5jsCEnrVzDQoU5tg63njLNy0UTDNAD949NSQ00 |title=Skinheads plead not guilty in alleged Obama plot |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |date=2009-11-06 |accessdate=2008-11-07}}{{Dead link|date=November 2012|bot=Legobot}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n | quote  = \"They sound crazy, like a really bad movie{{spaced ndash}}Quentin Tarantino gone awry. You listen to that, and you say, 'In a hundred thousand years, they never would have reached Obama.' But the reality is, they might have walked into a black high school and killed 20, 30, 40 people before anybody knew who they were.\"\n | source = '''Mark Potok, director of the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]]'''<ref name=\"WP0111\">{{Citation |last=Johnson |first=Carrie |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/10/AR2009011002039_2.html?hpid=moreheadlines |title=Bad Economy May Fuel Hate Groups, Experts Warn |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2009-01-11 |accessdate=2009-01-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107100929/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/10/AR2009011002039_2.html?hpid=moreheadlines |archive-date=2012-11-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n | align = left\n| width = 195px\n }}\nFred Fielder, police chief in Helena\u2013West Helena, Arkansas, said the alleged plot in Tennessee particularly concerned him due to the fact that 66 percent of the city's 12,200 population are African American; he said to reporters, \"Predominantly black school, take your pick.\"<ref name=\"AP1027\" /> Mark Potok, director of the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]], described the plans and weapons arsenal as frightening, but said, \"With the part about wearing top hats&nbsp;... it gets a bit hard to take them seriously.\"<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> Nevertheless, Potok said \"the reality is, they might have walked into a black high school and killed 20, 30, 40 people before anybody knew who they were\".<ref name=\"WP0111\" /> An editorial in ''[[The Daily News Journal]]'' in [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee]], said the plot emphasized a dark undercurrent of racism still alive in the United States, but said their chances  of actually killing Obama were \"almost nil. Their plot was so disorganized they appear to be candidates for 'dumb criminals', not calculating assassins.\"<ref>[http://www.dnj.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081030/OPINION01/810300305 \"Editorial: Foiled plot revives pain of racism.\"]{{dead link|date=December 2015}} ''[[The Daily News Journal]]'', October 30, 2008. Retrieved on 2008-11-07.</ref>\n\nDespite initial concerns about the plot, the Obama campaign was not immediately notified of the alleged plot; an Obama aide told [[ABC News]], \"They were given no heads up.\"<ref>{{Citation |last= Stephanopoulos |first=George |author-link=George Stephanopoulos |url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/george/2008/10/obama-agents-no.html |title=Obama not told about alleged assassination plot. |newspaper=[[ABC News]] |date=2008-10-27 |accessdate=2008-10-28| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081030012237/http://blogs.abcnews.com/george/2008/10/obama-agents-no.html| archivedate= 30 October 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> Concerns were already strong about possible plots against Obama due to his status as the first African American presidential nominee for a major political party. The senator had been receiving Secret Service protection since May 2007, which was the earliest for any candidate, and authorities had already foiled an [[Barack Obama assassination plot in Denver|alleged assassination plot]] at the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]] in [[Denver]], [[Colorado]].<ref name=\"NYT1027\" />\n\n==Histories of plotters==\n\n===Paul Schlesselman===\nPaul Schlesselman is of [[German-American|German descent]] and was a high school dropout raised by a single father in [[Helena\u2013West Helena, Arkansas]]. He hated his small [[Arkansas Delta|Delta]] region hometown because of its predominantly black population. He had never had any problems with the law prior to the alleged Obama plot. He had a strong affinity for drinking and smoking.<ref name=\"ArkDemGaz1029\">{{Citation |last=Krupa |first=John |url=http://m.arkansasonline.com/news/2008/oct/29/teen-plot-lists-drinking-his-job-20081029/ |title=Teen in plot lists drinking as his job |newspaper=[[Arkansas Democrat-Gazette]] |date=2008-10-29 |accessdate=2010-01-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707162133/http://m.arkansasonline.com/news/2008/oct/29/teen-plot-lists-drinking-his-job-20081029/ |archive-date=2011-07-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSchlesselman publicly claimed white people were the [[master race]] and would often say \"[[Sieg Heil]]\" and \"[[Heil Hitler]].\"<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> He spoke out against Obama, saying things like, \"Obama would make the world suffer.\"<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> His [[Anti-racism|anti-racist]] sister Kayla, who is two years younger than Paul, often argued with him about his racial beliefs. A few days before his arrest, a neighbor said he heard semiautomatic gunfire coming from an open field behind Schlesselman's house.<ref name=\"ArkDemGaz1029\" /> After his arrest, Schlesselman's family expressed doubt that he seriously intended to carry out the plot; his father, Mike, said, \"I think it's just a lot of talk. He would never do something like this.\"<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> Kayla said she spoke with her brother after the charges were made public, and that Paul \"said he's sorry about everything he's done.\"<ref name=\"AP1030\" />\n\n===Daniel Cowart===\nDaniel Cowart is of [[English-Americans|English descent]] and was raised in [[Bells, Tennessee]]. He had a strong interest in computers and had no criminal record. Cowart attended [[Jackson Christian School]] until 2006, but did not graduate.  He was expelled from Jackson Christian after calling in a bomb threat. He applied for [[Jackson State Community College]] to study computers but, although his family believed he was indeed attending the school, he never provided documentation or pursued other steps to enroll there. Cowart moved to [[Texas]] in the spring of 2007 to live with friends he met on the Internet, but was unable to find work and returned to Bells to live with his grandparents a month later.<ref name=\"Jackson1029\">{{Citation |last=Martin |first=Mariann |title=Image of Daniel Cowart not familiar to those he knew in Bells |newspaper=[[The Jackson Sun]] |date=2008-10-29}}</ref> Cowart worked at a Bells grocery store called the Bells Market Place for one year until May 2007 before moving to Texas for a brief time. Cowart worked and got along with several minority co-workers, who later expressed shock at his arrest. Mitchell Twitty, a black former co-worker, said of Cowart, \"He treated me like we were best friends. I never, ever heard him make a racist remark.\"<ref name=\"Jackson1030\">{{Citation |last=Martin |first=Mariann |title=Minority coworkers say Cowart was always friendly, respectful. |newspaper=[[The Jackson Sun]] |date=2008-10-30}}</ref> Twitty said Cowart tended to keep to himself and at times acted \"a little strange.\"<ref name=\"Jackson1030\" /> Other co-workers described him as hard-working and friendly, but said he did not have many friends. One family friend thought he was intelligent and full of potential: \"I always saw him as a doctor or lawyer, or even a senator. He even had the potential to become what Obama is, running for president.\"<ref name=\"Jackson1030\" />\n\nAccording to the Southern Poverty Law Center, Cowart belonged to the Supreme White Alliance, a white supremacist group. A photograph of Cowart celebrating the birthday of [[Adolf Hitler]] with other members was on the group's website.<ref name=\"AP1030\" /> On the group's social networking site, Cowart described himself as \"easygoing and easy to get along with, as long as you are white!\"<ref name=\"ArkDemGaz1029\" /> Cowart was allegedly kicked out of the group sometime prior to his arrest. The club's president, Steve Edwards of [[Central City, Kentucky]], resigned due to the negative press following Cowart's arrest. Although Edwards acknowledged Cowart's membership, he said the group had no part in the plan, and claimed that the media exaggerated Cowart's connection to the group.<ref name=\"AP1030\" />\n\n==Trials==\n[[Image:Schlesselmancowarttrial.jpg|thumb|A court drawing of the first hearing and not guilty pleas of Paul Schlesselman (middle) and Daniel Cowart (right)]]\nA grand jury indicted Paul Schlesselman and Daniel Cowart on November 5, 2008, on federal charges of threatening to kill and inflict bodily harm upon a major presidential candidate, conspiracy, interstate unlawful transportation of an unregistered firearm, interstate transportation of a firearm with the intent to commit a felony, transporting a short-barreled shotgun across state lines without a license and unlawful possession of a short-barreled shotgun. Cowart was also charged with damaging religious property and use of a firearm during a crime of violence.<ref>{{Citation |last=Martin |first=Mariann |title=2 men charged in Obama plot face additional counts |newspaper=[[The Jackson Sun]] |date=2008-11-21}}</ref> On November 6, Schlesselman and Cowart pleaded not guilty before a federal magistrate in [[Memphis, Tennessee]]. The two were placed into federal custody without bail. The charges carry a maximum punishment of 50 years in prison and $540,000 in fines.<ref name=\"AP1106\" />\n\nAt the request of federal authorities, the men were placed on [[lockdown]] in their [[Obion County, Tennessee]], jail cell for their own safety. The two men could leave their cell for only one hour to watch television or use the phone; authorities said they had caused no problems during their time in the jail.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5jsCEnrVzDQoU5tg63njLNy0UTDNAD94BP9TG0 |title=2 accused of threatening Obama kept on lockdown |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |date=2008-11-09 |accessdate=2008-11-10}}{{Dead link|date=November 2012|bot=Legobot}}</ref>\n\nCowart's lawyer argued in a November 13 petition that the grand jury was racially stacked against him because it included only two white members, while \"21 were African-American or of another race or races\".<ref name=\"AP1113\" /> Cowart's attorney argued his indictment should be dismissed because jury could not \"under the most modest constitutional scrutiny&nbsp;... be considered fair, impartial and unprejudiced.\"<ref name=\"AP1113\" /> In February 2009, a federal judge granted Schlesselman and Cowart limited access to court records on the grand jury selection and gave them permission to question procedures for selecting jurors. However, their defense attorneys were not allowed to challenge the resulting racial makeup of the actual jury.<ref>{{Citation |last=Chism |first=Michelle |url=http://www.todaysthv.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=79876&catid=2 |title=Arkansan Charged In Skinhead Plot Granted Access To Court Records |date=2009-02-09 |accessdate=2009-02-09 |newspaper=[[KTHV]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090821022841/http://www.todaysthv.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=79876&catid=2 |archive-date=2009-08-21 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also in February 2009, Schlesselman's lawyer asked the court to dismiss statements he previously gave police and evidence that he contended was wrongfully seized during searches of his home and another residence.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.waaytv.com/Global/story.asp?S=9843627 |title=Man accused in Obama plot wants evidence tossed |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |date=2009-02-14 |accessdate=2009-02-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217234641/http://www.waaytv.com/global/story.asp?s=9843627 |archive-date=2009-02-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Judge [[J. Daniel Breen]] of the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Tennessee]] refused this request in April.<ref>{{Citation|title=Judge Won't Toss Evidence in Plot Against Obama - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=2009-06-08}}</ref> Schlesselman's counsel argued his assassination threat charges should be dropped because he said the alleged comments were made while in custody, so he could not have carried them out and they were not a \"true threat\". Judge Breen rejected that argument in March 2009.<ref>{{Citation|last=Buser |first=Lawrence |title=Judge refuses to dismiss charge in Obama threat |date=2009-03-25 |work=[[The Commercial Appeal]] |location=Memphis, Tennessee |url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2009/mar/25/judge-refuses-dismiss-charge-obama-threat/ |accessdate=2009-03-27 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531054556/http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2009/mar/25/judge-refuses-dismiss-charge-obama-threat/ |archivedate=2009-05-31 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{Wikinews|Judge refuses to dismiss charge against Barack Obama assassination plotter}}\nThe prosecution asked for two separate trials, which were expected to take place in [[Jackson, Tennessee]], the area where the alleged crimes occurred.<ref name=\"AP1113\">{{Citation |last=Baird |first=Woody |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/11/13/national/main4601657.shtml |title=Man charged in Obama plot says grand jury skewed |newspaper=CBS |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=2008-11-13 |accessdate=2008-11-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101115154856/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/11/13/national/main4601657.shtml |archive-date=2010-11-15 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/jacksonsun/access/1866154531.html?FMT=ABS&amp;date=Sep+12,+2009 | work=The Jackson Sun | first=Mariann | last=Martin | title=Separate trials sought in alleged Obama plot | date=2009-09-12 | access-date=2020-01-30 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024133434/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/jacksonsun/access/1866154531.html?FMT=ABS&date=Sep+12,+2009 | archive-date=2012-10-24 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Guilty pleas and sentencing==\nSchlesselman pleaded guilty to two counts in the indictment against him plus one count of an information on January 14, 2010, with an agreed-upon sentence of ten years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2010/jan/14/skinhead-pleads-guilty-conspiring-kill-black-peopl |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615175713/http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2010/jan/14/skinhead-pleads-guilty-conspiring-kill-black-peopl |archivedate=June 15, 2011 |url-status=dead |title='Skinhead' pleads guilty to conspiring to kill black people, threatening Obama |work=commercialappeal.com |author=Staff writer |date=January 14, 2010}}</ref> Cowart pleaded guilty to eight of the nine counts in the superseding indictment on March 29, 2010.<ref>{{Citation |last=Dunlap |first=Stanley |title=Obama plot suspect enters plea |date=2010-03-29 |newspaper=[[The Jackson Sun|Jackson Sun]]}}</ref> On April 15, 2010, Judge Breen sentenced Schlesselman to 10 years in federal prison.<ref>{{cite web|title=Obama assassination plot: Paul Schlesselman sentenced to 10 years for plotting murder spree|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/2010/0/16/2010-04-16_obama_assassination_plot_paul_schlesselman_sentenced_to_10_years_for_plotting_mu.html|work=New York Daily News|accessdate=January 9, 2011|date=April 16, 2010}}{{dead link|date=December 2015}}</ref> Judge Breen sentenced Cowart to 14 years in prison on October 22, 2010.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://memphis.fbi.gov/dojpressrel/pressrel10/me102210.htm |title=Tennessee Man Sentenced for Conspiring to Commit Murders of African-Americans |publisher=Federal Bureau of Investigation, Memphis |date=October 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20110805165411/http://memphis.fbi.gov/dojpressrel/pressrel10/me102210.htm |archivedate=August 5, 2011 }}</ref> The U.S. Justice Department said that Cowart could have been sentenced to a maximum 75 years, and Cowart was originally to be sentenced on August 13.<ref>{{cite web|title=Man who plotted to kill Obama to be sentenced |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2010-08-13/justice/tennessee.obama.plot_1_paul-schlesselman-daniel-cowart-west-helena?_s=PM:CRIME |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100915063447/http://articles.cnn.com/2010-08-13/justice/tennessee.obama.plot_1_paul-schlesselman-daniel-cowart-west-helena?_s=PM%3ACRIME |archivedate=September 15, 2010 |url-status=dead |publisher=CNN |date=August 13, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Incarceration==\nSchlesselman served his sentence at the medium-security [[Federal Correctional Institution, McKean|Federal Correctional Institution in McKean, Pennsylvania]], and was released in July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inmate locator: Paul Schlesselman |url=http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=NameSearch&needingMoreList=false&FirstName=paul&Middle=&LastName=schlesselman&Race=U&Sex=U&Age=&x=0&y=0 |publisher=Federal Bureau of Prisons |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629182205/http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=NameSearch&needingMoreList=false&FirstName=paul&Middle=&LastName=schlesselman&Race=U&Sex=U&Age=&x=0&y=0 |archivedate=June 29, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Cowart is serving his sentence at the medium-security [[Federal Correctional Institution, Williamsburg|Federal Correctional Institution in Williamsburg, South Carolina]], and is scheduled for release in 2021.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inmate locator: Register #22540-076 |url=http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=22540-076&x=56&y=20 |publisher=Federal Bureau of Prisons |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629182214/http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=22540-076&x=56&y=20 |archivedate=June 29, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/barackobama/5967942/Barack-Obama-faces-30-death-threats-a-day-stretching-US-Secret-Service.html Barack Obama Faces 30 Death Threats a day, Stretching US Secret Service] by Toby Harnden, ''Daily Telegraph'', August 3, 2009\n{{Barack Obama}}\n{{Neo-Nazism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barack Obama Assassination Plot In Tennessee}}\n[[Category:2008 in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Attempted assassinations of Presidents of the United States|Obama]]\n[[Category:Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|Assassination plot in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Crimes in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Neo-Nazism in the United States]]\n[[Category:October 2008 crimes]]\n[[Category:Terrorism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in the United States in 2008]]\n[[Category:White nationalism in the United States]]\n[[Category:White nationalist terrorism]]\n[[Category:White supremacy in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "RFalls", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAssessment of threat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barack_Obama_assassination_plot_in_Tennessee"}
{"title_page": "List of largest daily changes in the Dow Jones Industrial Average", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Current related||2020 stock market crash|date=March 2020}}\nThis is a '''list of the largest daily changes''' in the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] from 1896. Compare to the [[list of largest daily changes in the S&P 500 Index]].\n\n== Largest point changes ==\n\nThe first four tables show only the largest one-day changes between a given day's close and the close of the previous [[trading day]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://online.wsj.com/mdc/public/page/2_3047-djia_alltime.html|title=Historical Index Data All-Time Largest One Day Gains and Losses|work=wsj.com|access-date=March 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219114148/http://online.wsj.com/mdc/public/page/2_3047-djia_alltime.html|archive-date=February 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[http://www.djindexes.com/mdsidx/downloads/xlspages/high_low_lights.xls Highlights/Lowlights of The Dow] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080920224647/http://www.djindexes.com/mdsidx/downloads/xlspages/high_low_lights.xls |date=September 20, 2008 }} (Excel spreadsheet)</ref> not the largest changes during the trading day (i.e. intraday changes). \n\nThe Dow Jones Industrial Average was first published in 1896, but since the firms listed at that time were in existence before then, the index can be calculated going back to May 2, 1881.<ref>CSV data file from http://finance.yahoo.com {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726035646/https://finance.yahoo.com/ |date=July 26, 2019 }}</ref> A loss of just over 24 percent on May 5, 1893 from 39.90 to 30.02 signaled the apex of the stock effects of the [[Panic of 1893]]; the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2008\u201309 crash]] was a 61.8 percent retracement thereof that began on October 11, 2007 and lasted until the closing low on March 9, 2009.<ref>DJIA_C.xls from same data</ref>\n\nThe largest point drop in history occurred on March 16, 2020, when concerns over the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] engulfed the market, dropping the Dow Jones Industrial Average 2,997 points. The largest point gain (+2,113) occurred on March 24, 2020. As of April 6, 2020, all of the top five and eight of the top ten largest point drops have been amid the [[2020 stock market crash]]. Likewise, eight of the top ten point gains, including all of the top five, have been during that crash, which has been marked by extreme point swings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/13/stocks-are-expected-to-see-more-wild-swings-even-if-fed-makes-big-policy-move.html|title=Stocks are expected to see more wild swings, even if Fed makes big policy move|first=Patty|last=Domm|date=13 March 2020|work=CNBC}}</ref>\n\n<div class=\"mw-collapsible mw-shown\">\n{|\n\n| '''Largest daily point gains<ref name=\"Spindices\">{{Cite web|url=https://us.spindices.com/indexology/djia-and-sp-500/sizzlers-and-fizzlers|title=Sizzlers and Fizzlers|website=us.spindices.com|access-date=March 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316215849/https://us.spindices.com/indexology/djia-and-sp-500/sizzlers-and-fizzlers|archive-date=March 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"background:#9f6;text-align:right\"\n! rowspan=2 | Rank\n! rowspan=2 | Date\n! rowspan=2 | Close\n! colspan=2 | Change\n! rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\" align=\"center\"|Ref&nbsp;\n|-\n! Net !! %\n|-\n|1\n|2020-03-24\n|20,704.91\n| +2,112.98\n| +11.37\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/24/stock-market-live-updates-dow-futures-up-900-limit-up-hope-for-a-stimulus-deal.html|title=Stock market live updates: Dow soars 2,100 points, biggest jump in 80 years, stimulus close|last=Imbert|first=Yun Li,Jesse Pound,Fred|date=2020-03-24|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2\n| 2020-03-13\n| 23,185.62\n|  +1,985.00\n|  +9.36\n|<ref>{{cite web| \nur