tion|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Current related||2020 stock market crash|date=March 2020}}\nThis is a '''list of the largest daily changes''' in the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] from 1896. Compare to the [[list of largest daily changes in the S&P 500 Index]].\n\n== Largest point changes ==\n\nThe first four tables show only the largest one-day changes between a given day's close and the close of the previous [[trading day]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://online.wsj.com/mdc/public/page/2_3047-djia_alltime.html|title=Historical Index Data All-Time Largest One Day Gains and Losses|work=wsj.com|access-date=March 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219114148/http://online.wsj.com/mdc/public/page/2_3047-djia_alltime.html|archive-date=February 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[http://www.djindexes.com/mdsidx/downloads/xlspages/high_low_lights.xls Highlights/Lowlights of The Dow] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080920224647/http://www.djindexes.com/mdsidx/downloads/xlspages/high_low_lights.xls |date=September 20, 2008 }} (Excel spreadsheet)</ref> not the largest changes during the trading day (i.e. intraday changes). \n\nThe Dow Jones Industrial Average was first published in 1896, but since the firms listed at that time were in existence before then, the index can be calculated going back to May 2, 1881.<ref>CSV data file from http://finance.yahoo.com {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726035646/https://finance.yahoo.com/ |date=July 26, 2019 }}</ref> A loss of just over 24 percent on May 5, 1893 from 39.90 to 30.02 signaled the apex of the stock effects of the [[Panic of 1893]]; the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2008\u201309 crash]] was a 61.8 percent retracement thereof that began on October 11, 2007 and lasted until the closing low on March 9, 2009.<ref>DJIA_C.xls from same data</ref>\n\nThe largest point drop in history occurred on March 16, 2020, when concerns over the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] engulfed the market, dropping the Dow Jones Industrial Average 2,997 points. The largest point gain (+2,113) occurred on March 24, 2020. As of March 26, 2020, all of the top five and eight of the top ten largest point drops have been amid the [[2020 stock market crash]]. Likewise, seven of the top ten point gains, including all of the top five, have been during that crash, which has been marked by extreme point swings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/13/stocks-are-expected-to-see-more-wild-swings-even-if-fed-makes-big-policy-move.html|title=Stocks are expected to see more wild swings, even if Fed makes big policy move|first=Patty|last=Domm|date=13 March 2020|work=CNBC}}</ref>\n\n<div class=\"mw-collapsible mw-shown\">\n{|\n\n| '''Largest daily point gains<ref name=\"Spindices\">{{Cite web|url=https://us.spindices.com/indexology/djia-and-sp-500/sizzlers-and-fizzlers|title=Sizzlers and Fizzlers|website=us.spindices.com|access-date=March 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316215849/https://us.spindices.com/indexology/djia-and-sp-500/sizzlers-and-fizzlers|archive-date=March 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"background:#9f6;text-align:right\"\n! rowspan=2 | Rank\n! rowspan=2 | Date\n! rowspan=2 | Close\n! colspan=2 | Change\n! rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\" align=\"center\"|Ref&nbsp;\n|-\n! Net !! %\n|-\n|1\n|2020-03-24\n|20,704.91\n| +2,112.98\n| +11.37\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/24/stock-market-live-updates-dow-futures-up-900-limit-up-hope-for-a-stimulus-deal.html|title=Stock market live updates: Dow soars 2,100 points, biggest jump in 80 years, stimulus close|last=Imbert|first=Yun Li,Jesse Pound,Fred|date=2020-03-24|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2\n| 2020-03-13\n| 23,185.62\n|  +1,985.00\n|  +9.36\n|<ref>{{cite web| \nurl=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/stock-futures-fall-again-indicating-ominous-start-to-trading-on-friday-the-