]]\n*[[Premiership Rugby]]\n*[[RFU Championship]]\n*[[National League 1]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Other sources==\n*''The Times'' newspaper 1984 onwards. News articles and results section.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090201055007/http://moseleyrugby.co.uk/%5E%20CLUB_HISTORY/CLUB_HISTORY.htm Moseley's history featuring many of the tables for the above leagues]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of The English Rugby Union System}}\n[[Category:Rugby union leagues in England| ]]\n[[Category:History of rugby union in England|Leagues]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1997\u201398 season:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1997-98 \u2192 1997\u201398", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_English_rugby_union_system"}
{"title_page": "Abraham M. Lurie", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Abraham M. Lurie\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = 1923\n| birth_place = [[Iowa]]\n| birth_name  = \n| death_date  = {{death year and age|2010|1923}}\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| residence   = \n| nationality = United States\n| education   = B.A. [[Ohio State University]]<br> J.D. [[UCLA School of Law]]\n| occupation  = real estate developer\n| known_for   = development of [[Marina del Rey]]\n| networth    = \n| children    = 4\n| spouse      = Katherine Lurie\n| parents     = \n| family      =\n| website     =\n }}\n\n'''Abraham M. Lurie''' (1923 \u2013 June 29, 2010) was an American real estate developer who was behind the development of much of [[Marina del Rey]].<ref name=Argo>[http://argonautnews.com/former-prominent-marina-del-rey-developer-abraham-lurie-dies-at-86/ The Argonaut: \"Former Prominent Marina Del Rey Developer Abraham Lurie Dies at 86\"] July 8, 2010</ref><ref name=LATimeBank>[http://articles.latimes.com/1991-06-13/news/we-925_1_marina-properties Los Angeles Times: \"Biggest Marina Developer Files for Bankruptcy : Finances: Abraham M. Lurie seeks court protection as he battles his Saudi partners for control of his extensive holdings\" by Jeffrey L. Rabin] June 13, 1991</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nLurie was born to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family in Iowa in 1923.<ref name=Argo /> He had two siblings: Dr. William Lurie and Bertha Lurie Friedman.<ref name=Argo /> He graduated with a B.A. in accounting from [[Ohio State University]] with a degree in accounting.<ref name=Argo /> In 1948 he moved to California where he worked as a certified public accountant and attended the [[UCLA School of Law]].<ref name=Argo /> In 1957, he passed the bar exam.<ref name=Argo />\n\n==Career==\nHe founded Real Property Management which was the single largest developer of the city of Marina del Rey.<ref name=LATimeBank /> In 1953, the Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors authorized a $2 million loan to fund the construction of the marina and on April 10, 1965 the Marina was completed.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1989-11-12/news/mn-2321_1_marina-del-rey Los Angeles Times: \"Marina del Rey Development Rose Out of Mud (First Of Two Parts)] November 12, 1989</ref> Soon after, the County solicited bids for its development. In 1968, Lurie purchased a 60-year lease from Los Angeles County which gave him the right to build on 20 percent of the land.<ref name=LATimeBank /> He went on to build  three hotels, two apartment complexes, 1,000 boat slips, and several shopping centers, offices, restaurants; his holdings also included the last undeveloped piece of waterfront land in Marina del Rey.<ref name=LATimeBank />\n\nAfter having cash flow problems<ref name=Jurist>[http://openjurist.org/57/f3d/1077/marina-international-properties-ltd-lurie-v-a-halderman In re MARINA INTERNATIONAL PROPERTIES, LTD., Debtor, Abraham M. LURIE, Appellant, v. Richard A. HALDERMAN, Jr., Trustee; Bank of Montreal; Marina Group of Companies, Appellees\"]</ref> Lurie sold a 49.9% interest in 1989 in his Marina holdings to Saudi billionaire [[Abdul Aziz Al-Ibrahim]] (brother of [[Waleed bin Ibrahim Al Ibrahim]] and brother-in-law of King [[Fahd of Saudi Arabia]]) and several other unnamed foreign investors, forming Marina International Properties Ltd.<ref name=LATimeBank /> The transaction was approved by the Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors despite not disclosing the identity of the investors<ref name=LATimeBank /> and included the Marina Beach, Marina International and Marina del Rey hotels, the Admiralty and Islander apartments, Fisherman's Village, Pier 44, Marina Beach Shopping Center and Marina West office complex.<ref name=LATimeBank /> The partnership required additional funds and in late 1990, an agreement was reached for Al-Ibrahim to buy out Lurie's interest but the deal soon fell apart and Al-Ibrahim sued to dissolve the partnership.<ref name=LATimeBank /> This caused $50 million in loans from four separate banks to default.<ref name=LATimeBank /> Al-Ibrahim accused Lurie of fraud, diversion of funds, and the failure of providing adequate financial reporting; and asked the judge to give him control of the Marina holdings.<ref name=LATimeBank /> Lurie counter-sued accusing Al-Ibrahim of withholding funds that were required to be transferred under the partnership putting the solvency of Marina International Properties Ltd. at risk.<ref name=LATimeBank /> Lurie was unsuccessful in finding outside investors who did not want to wade into the middle of a lawsuit with a deep-pocketed and connected Saudi<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1992-08-01/local/me-4251_1_real-estate-deal Los Angeles Times: \"A New Twist in Marina Bankruptcy Case : Real estate: Builder Jona Goldrich says he made no deal to aid Abraham M. Lurie, who is fighting his Saudi partner for control of properties\" by Jeffrey L. Rabin] August 01, 1992</ref> and petitioned the court to allow him to sell some of the leases without Al-Ibrahim's approval to pay off his bankers.<ref name=LATimeBank /> The court refused and Marina International Properties Ltd filed for bankruptcy.<ref name=LATimeBank />  The lawsuit was ultimately won by Al-Ibrahim who took over control of the partnership<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-01/local/me-29640_1_marina-del-rey Los Angeles Times: \"Saudi Wins Court Fight Over Marina : Real estate: Billionaire gains control of nearly 20% of county-owned Marina del Rey. Ruling ends Abraham Lurie's involvement\" by Jeffrey L. Rabin and Ron Russell] May 01, 1993</ref> and settled the then $140 million in debt outstanding.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1983, he married Katherine Lurie.<ref>[http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/latimes/obituary.aspx?pid=143945167 Los Angeles Times: \"Abraham Lurie\"] July 6, 2010</ref> He had four children: Leslie Beck, Scott Lurie, Donald Schneider and Thomas Carlyle.<ref name=Argo /> He died on June 29, 2010; services were held at [[Mount Sinai Memorial Park Cemetery]] in [[Hollywood Hills]], [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=Argo />\n\nOn 4/5/2020 Abe's only son Scott noticed that his last Wife Kathrine never had a grave stone placed at his grave. What is up with that....?\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lurie, Abraham M.}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:American real estate businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Iowa]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Abraham M. Lurie\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = 1923\n| birth_place = [[Iowa]]\n| birth_name  = \n| death_date  = {{death year and age|2010|1923}}\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| residence   = \n| nationality = United States\n| education   = B.A. [[Ohio State University]]<br> J.D. [[UCLA School of Law]]\n| occupation  = real estate developer\n| known_for   = development of [[Marina del Rey]]\n| networth    = \n| children    = 4\n| spouse      = Katherine Lurie\n| parents     = \n| family      =\n| website     =\n }}\n\n'''Abraham M. Lurie''' (1923 \u2013 June 29, 2010) was an American real estate developer who was behind the development of much of [[Marina del Rey]].<ref name=Argo>[http://argonautnews.com/former-prominent-marina-del-rey-developer-abraham-lurie-dies-at-86/ The Argonaut: \"Former Prominent Marina Del Rey Developer Abraham Lurie Dies at 86\"] July 8, 2010</ref><ref name=LATimeBank>[http://articles.latimes.com/1991-06-13/news/we-925_1_marina-properties Los Angeles Times: \"Biggest Marina Developer Files for Bankruptcy : Finances: Abraham M. Lurie seeks court protection as he battles his Saudi partners for control of his extensive holdings\" by Jeffrey L. Rabin] June 13, 1991</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nLurie was born to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family in Iowa in 1923.<ref name=Argo /> He had two siblings: Dr. William Lurie and Bertha Lurie Friedman.<ref name=Argo /> He graduated with a B.A. in accounting from [[Ohio State University]] with a degree in accounting.<ref name=Argo /> In 1948 he moved to California where he worked as a certified public accountant and attended the [[UCLA School of Law]].<ref name=Argo /> In 1957, he passed the bar exam.<ref name=Argo />\n\n==Career==\nHe founded Real Property Management which was the single largest developer of the city of Marina del Rey.<ref name=LATimeBank /> In 1953, the Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors authorized a $2 million loan to fund the construction of the marina and on April 10, 1965 the Marina was completed.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1989-11-12/news/mn-2321_1_marina-del-rey Los Angeles Times: \"Marina del Rey Development Rose Out of Mud (First Of Two Parts)] November 12, 1989</ref> Soon after, the County solicited bids for its development. In 1968, Lurie purchased a 60-year lease from Los Angeles County which gave him the right to build on 20 percent of the land.<ref name=LATimeBank /> He went on to build  three hotels, two apartment complexes, 1,000 boat slips, and several shopping centers, offices, restaurants; his holdings also included the last undeveloped piece of waterfront land in Marina del Rey.<ref name=LATimeBank />\n\nAfter having cash flow problems<ref name=Jurist>[http://openjurist.org/57/f3d/1077/marina-international-properties-ltd-lurie-v-a-halderman In re MARINA INTERNATIONAL PROPERTIES, LTD., Debtor, Abraham M. LURIE, Appellant, v. Richard A. HALDERMAN, Jr., Trustee; Bank of Montreal; Marina Group of Companies, Appellees\"]</ref> Lurie sold a 49.9% interest in 1989 in his Marina holdings to Saudi billionaire [[Abdul Aziz Al-Ibrahim]] (brother of [[Waleed bin Ibrahim Al Ibrahim]] and brother-in-law of King [[Fahd of Saudi Arabia]]) and several other unnamed foreign investors, forming Marina International Properties Ltd.<ref name=LATimeBank /> The transaction was approved by the Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors despite not disclosing the identity of the investors<ref name=LATimeBank /> and included the Marina Beach, Marina International and Marina del Rey hotels, the Admiralty and Islander apartments, Fisherman's Village, Pier 44, Marina Beach Shopping Center and Marina West office complex.<ref name=LATimeBank /> The partnership required additional funds and in late 1990, an agreement was reached for Al-Ibrahim to buy out Lurie's interest but the deal soon fell apart and Al-Ibrahim sued to dissolve the partnership.<ref name=LATimeBank /> This caused $50 million in loans from four separate banks to default.<ref name=LATimeBank /> Al-Ibrahim accused Lurie of fraud, diversion of funds, and the failure of providing adequate financial reporting; and asked the judge to give him control of the Marina holdings.<ref name=LATimeBank /> Lurie counter-sued accusing Al-Ibrahim of withholding funds that were required to be transferred under the partnership putting the solvency of Marina International Properties Ltd. at risk.<ref name=LATimeBank /> Lurie was unsuccessful in finding outside investors who did not want to wade into the middle of a lawsuit with a deep-pocketed and connected Saudi<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1992-08-01/local/me-4251_1_real-estate-deal Los Angeles Times: \"A New Twist in Marina Bankruptcy Case : Real estate: Builder Jona Goldrich says he made no deal to aid Abraham M. Lurie, who is fighting his Saudi partner for control of properties\" by Jeffrey L. Rabin] August 01, 1992</ref> and petitioned the court to allow him to sell some of the leases without Al-Ibrahim's approval to pay off his bankers.<ref name=LATimeBank /> The court refused and Marina International Properties Ltd filed for bankruptcy.<ref name=LATimeBank />  The lawsuit was ultimately won by Al-Ibrahim who took over control of the partnership<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-01/local/me-29640_1_marina-del-rey Los Angeles Times: \"Saudi Wins Court Fight Over Marina : Real estate: Billionaire gains control of nearly 20% of county-owned Marina del Rey. Ruling ends Abraham Lurie's involvement\" by Jeffrey L. Rabin and Ron Russell] May 01, 1993</ref> and settled the then $140 million in debt outstanding.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1983, he married Katherine Lurie.<ref>[http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/latimes/obituary.aspx?pid=143945167 Los Angeles Times: \"Abraham Lurie\"] July 6, 2010</ref> He had four children: Leslie Beck, Scott Lurie, Donald Schneider and Thomas Carlyle.<ref name=Argo /> He died on June 29, 2010; services were held at [[Mount Sinai Memorial Park Cemetery]] in [[Hollywood Hills]], [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=Argo />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lurie, Abraham M.}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:American real estate businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Iowa]]\n", "name_user": "SMSScott", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:noticed no grave stone", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abraham_M._Lurie"}
{"title_page": "Maxim Akimov", "text_new": "{{short description|Russian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Maxim Akimov\n| image   = Maxim_Akimov_official_portrait.png\n| imagesize =\n| caption =\n| native_name = \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043c \u0410\u043a\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432\n| native_name_lang = ru\n| office = [[Deputy Prime Minister of Russia|Deputy Prime Minister]] for Transport, Communications\nand Digital Economy\n| primeminister = [[Dmitry Medvedev]]\n| term_start = 18 May 2018\n| term_end = 15 January 2020<br><small> [[Acting (law)|Acting]]: 15 January 2020 \u2013 present</small>\n| office2 = Vice Governor of [[Kaluga Oblast]]\n| governor2= [[Anatoly Artamonov]]\n| term_start2 = July 2007\n| term_end2 = May 2012\n| office3 = Mayor of [[Kaluga]]\n| predecessor3 = Valery Ivanov\n| successor3 = [[Nikolay Lyubimov]]\n| term_start3 = 14 November 2004\n| term_end3 = July 2007\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|3|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Maloyaroslavets]], [[Kaluga Oblast]], [[Soviet Union]] (now [[Russia]])\n| death_date =\n| death_place      = \n| restingplace     = \n| party = [[United Russia]]\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Kaluga State University]]\n| spouse = \n| nationality = [[Russians|Russian]]\n| religion= \n| children = 2\n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Maxim Alexeevich Akimov''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043c \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0410\u043a\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432}}; born 1 March 1970) is a Russian politician. He served as the [[Deputy Prime Minister of Russia]] from 2018\u20132020.<ref>[http://tass.ru/encyclopedia/person/%D0%90/akimov-maksim-alekseevich \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0422\u0410\u0421\u0421]</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAkimov was born in the city of [[Maloyaroslavets]], in [[Kaluga Oblast]].<ref>[https://ria.ru/spravka/20120601/662785297.html \u0411\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043c\u0430 \u0410\u043a\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0430]</ref>\n\nIn 1993 he graduated from [[Kaluga State University]].\n\nFrom 1994 to 1996, he was the CEO of the Faynart-Audit company, then headed the Commission for the Securities Market of the Kaluga Oblast. From 1998 to 2001, he served as the Deputy Director of the Department of Economy and Industry of Kaluga Oblast.\n\nIn 2004, he served as the Minister of Economic Development of Kaluga Oblast. In May 2004, he went to work for the municipal Government of Kaluga as the First Deputy Mayor. He later became acting Mayor. On 14 November 2004, he was elected as Mayor of Kaluga with 34.63% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0410\u043a\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432, \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043c \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u0440\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \u0410\u043f\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0420\u0424 - \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0422\u0410\u0421\u0421|url=http://tass.ru/encyclopedia/person/%D0%90/akimov-maksim-alekseevich|work=\u0422\u0410\u0421\u0421|accessdate=2017-12-16|language=ru}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2007, he was appointed Deputy Governor of Kaluga Oblast [[Anatoly Artamonov]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kaluga24.tv/maksim-akimov-naznachen-pervyim-zamestitelem-rukovoditelya-apparata-pravitelstva-rf/|title=\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043c \u0410\u043a\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u043c \u0437\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043c \u0440\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \u0430\u043f\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0420\u0424|author=|website=Kaluga24.tv|date=2013-05-23|publisher=|language=ru|accessdate=2017-12-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 May 2012 he was appointed Deputy Chief of Staff of the [[Government of Russia]]. A year later, he took the place of First Deputy Chief of Staff.\n\nOn 7 May 2018, he was nominated for the post of Deputy Prime Minister for Transport, Communications and Digital Economy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ria.ru/politics/20180507/1520072692.html|title=\u041c\u0435\u0434\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043b \u043a\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u0434\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0432 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430|work=\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|access-date=2018-05-07|language=ru}}</ref> On 15 January 2020, he resigned as part of the cabinet, after [[President of Russia|President]] [[Vladimir Putin]] delivered the [[Presidential Address to the Federal Assembly]], in which he proposed several amendments to the constitution.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/dmitry-medvedev-resign-russia-prime-minister-putin-quit-latest-a9284741.html |title=Russian PM resigns in shock move as Putin announces dramatic constitutional shake-up |last=Carroll |first=Oliver |date=January 15, 2020 |website=The Independent |language=en |access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMaxim Akimov is married. He has two sons.<ref>[http://government.ru/gov/persons/207/bio/ \u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Russian Cabinet}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akimov, Maxim}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Maloyaroslavetsky District]]\n[[Category:United Russia politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Russian politicians]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Kaluga]]\n[[Category:Russian historians]]\n[[Category:Deputy heads of government of the Russian Federation]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Russian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox Minister\n| name = Maxim Akimov\n| image   = Maxim_Akimov_official_portrait.png\n| imagesize =\n| caption =\n| native_name = \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043c \u0410\u043a\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432\n| native_name_lang = ru\n| office = [[Deputy Prime Minister of Russia|Deputy Prime Minister]] for Transport, Communications\nand Digital Economy\n| primeminister = [[Dmitry Medvedev]]\n| term_start = 18 May 2018\n| term_end = 15 January 2020<br><small> [[Acting (law)|Acting]]: 15 January 2020 \u2013 present</small>\n| office2 = Vice Governor of [[Kaluga Oblast]]\n| governor2= [[Anatoly Artamonov]]\n| term_start2 = July 2007\n| term_end2 = May 2012\n| office3 = Mayor of [[Kaluga]]\n| predecessor3 = Valery Ivanov\n| successor3 = [[Nikolay Lyubimov]]\n| term_start3 = 14 November 2004\n| term_end3 = July 2007\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|3|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Maloyaroslavets]], [[Kaluga Oblast]], [[Soviet Union]] (now [[Russia]])\n| death_date =\n| death_place      = \n| restingplace     = \n| party = [[United Russia]]\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Kaluga State University]]\n| spouse = \n| nationality = [[Russians|Russian]]\n| religion= \n| children = 2\n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Maxim Alexeevich Akimov''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043c \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0410\u043a\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432}}; born 1 March 1970) is a Russian politician. He served as the [[Deputy Prime Minister of Russia]] from 2018\u20132020.<ref>[http://tass.ru/encyclopedia/person/%D0%90/akimov-maksim-alekseevich \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0422\u0410\u0421\u0421]</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nAkimov was born in the city of [[Maloyaroslavets]], in [[Kaluga Oblast]].<ref>[https://ria.ru/spravka/20120601/662785297.html \u0411\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043c\u0430 \u0410\u043a\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0430]</ref>\n\nIn 1993 he graduated from [[Kaluga State University]].\n\nFrom 1994 to 1996, he was the CEO of the Faynart-Audit company, then headed the Commission for the Securities Market of the Kaluga Oblast. From 1998 to 2001, he served as the Deputy Director of the Department of Economy and Industry of Kaluga Oblast.\n\nIn 2004, he served as the Minister of Economic Development of Kaluga Oblast. In May 2004, he went to work for the municipal Government of Kaluga as the First Deputy Mayor. He later became acting Mayor. On 14 November 2004, he was elected as Mayor of Kaluga with 34.63% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0410\u043a\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432, \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043c \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u0440\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \u0410\u043f\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0420\u0424 - \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0422\u0410\u0421\u0421|url=http://tass.ru/encyclopedia/person/%D0%90/akimov-maksim-alekseevich|work=\u0422\u0410\u0421\u0421|accessdate=2017-12-16|language=ru}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2007, he was appointed Deputy Governor of Kaluga Oblast [[Anatoly Artamonov]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kaluga24.tv/maksim-akimov-naznachen-pervyim-zamestitelem-rukovoditelya-apparata-pravitelstva-rf/|title=\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043c \u0410\u043a\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u043c \u0437\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043c \u0440\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \u0430\u043f\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0420\u0424|author=|website=Kaluga24.tv|date=2013-05-23|publisher=|language=ru|accessdate=2017-12-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 May 2012 he was appointed Deputy Chief of Staff of the [[Government of Russia]]. A year later, he took the place of First Deputy Chief of Staff.\n\nOn 7 May 2018, he was nominated for the post of Deputy Prime Minister for Transport, Communications and Digital Economy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ria.ru/politics/20180507/1520072692.html|title=\u041c\u0435\u0434\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043b \u043a\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u0434\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0432 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430|work=\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|access-date=2018-05-07|language=ru}}</ref> On 15 January 2020, he resigned as part of the cabinet, after [[President of Russia|President]] [[Vladimir Putin]] delivered the [[Presidential Address to the Federal Assembly]], in which he proposed several amendments to the constitution.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/dmitry-medvedev-resign-russia-prime-minister-putin-quit-latest-a9284741.html |title=Russian PM resigns in shock move as Putin announces dramatic constitutional shake-up |last=Carroll |first=Oliver |date=January 15, 2020 |website=The Independent |language=en |access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMaxim Akimov is married. He has two sons.<ref>[http://government.ru/gov/persons/207/bio/ \u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Russian Cabinet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akimov, Maxim}}\n[[Category:19